I fixed it by generating a base64 zip instead of uint8array.

Before:
```
var JSZip = require(&quot;jszip&quot;);
var zip = new JSZip();

const myZip = await zip.generateAsync({
                type: &#39;uint8array&#39;,
                base64: true,
                compression: &#39;DEFLATE&#39;
            });
```
After:
```
var JSZip = require(&quot;jszip&quot;);
var zip = new JSZip();

const myZip = await zip.generateAsync({type: &#39;base64&#39;});
```

If you&#39;re only interested in numbers, it&#39;s odd to store them in cells... To use a function like `ismember` you&#39;ll have to deploy `cell2mat`. Then this gives your result:

    A = {{1,2,3};{2,3};{1,2,3};{2,3}};
    tgt = [2,3];
    cellfun( @(x) all( ismember( tgt, cell2mat(x) ) ), A )

If instead you stored the numbers in numeric arrays, this would be more efficient

    A = {[1,2,3];[2,3];[1,2,3];[2,3]};
    cellfun( @(x) all( ismember( tgt, x ) ), A )

