If you are using GNOME Shell &gt;= 3.32 you can use MetaSoundPlayer:

```js
const Gio = imports.gi.Gio;

let player = global.display.get_sound_player();

// Themed sound
player.play_from_theme(&#39;phone-incoming-call&#39;, &#39;arbitrary description&#39;, null);

// Sound File
let soundFile = Gio.File.new_for_path(&#39;/some/path/sound.ogg&#39;);
player.play_from_file(soundFile, &#39;arbitrary description&#39;, null);
```

Or there are global functions in GNOME Shell &lt;= 3.30 ([old docs](https://developer.gnome.org/shell/3.24/shell-shell-global.html#shell-global-play-theme-sound)):

```js
// Themed sound
global.play_theme_sound(0, &#39;phone-incoming-call&#39;, &#39;arbitrary description&#39;, null);


// File name
global.play_sound_file(0, &#39;/some/path/sound.ogg&#39;, &#39;arbitrary description&#39;, null);
```


There is a `gnome-shell` commit showing examples of both [here](https://github.com/GNOME/gnome-shell/commit/25bfe99ed53b5b700c589bb787f36a3be2ec8110).

If you&#39;re looking for user input you could use the following

    $input1 = Read-Host -Prompt &#39;input question&#39;
    $input2 = Read-Host -Prompt &#39;input question&#39;

That&#39;ll store $input1 and $input2 for the users input

PowerShell uses Write-host to output so following this

    write-host &quot;This is some &#39;$input1&#39; and some &#39;$input2&#39; text&quot;

